    homeStockPara: "Pre-war co-op apartments on the Upper East Side and prewar brownstones in Park Slope define the Manhattan and Brooklyn kitchen stock. Galley footprints of 70-110 sqft dominate these layouts, often with cast-iron radiators along one wall and a single exterior window that the board will not allow you to enlarge. Riverdale wartime construction and Forest Hills Tudor kitchens run larger but still show 1940s layouts with pantry closets that modern refrigerators cannot fit. Astoria two-families usually have a rear-facing eat-in that can expand only toward the yard.",
